{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491392"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"929"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/929"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.69,0.08,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32430"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/929"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"929"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"423"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32430"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old woman presents with a two week history of gradually deteriorating vision in her left eye. Her symptoms started with flashing lights and then a cloudy diminution in vision. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes for which she takes gliclazide and hypertension treated with captopril. A view of the left retina is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Central retinal artery occlusion","Central retinal vein occlusion","Retinal detachment","Hypertensive retinopathy","Diabetic retinopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe history of flashing lights along with \u0027wrinkling\u0027 of the retina supports a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eretinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E. This is an ocular emergency and requires urgent ophthalmological referral. The visual outcome, despite surgical reattachment, once the macula has detached with loss of central vision, is never as good.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentral retinal artery occlusion typically presents with acute onset of painless vision loss with the pale retina and a \u0027cherry red\u0027 spot. Central retinal vein occlusion shows a retina with flame and dot-blot haemorrhages throughout the retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypertensive retinopathy presents in a subacute fashion with the retina showing arteriolar narrowing, AV nipping, and copper/silver wiring. Diabetic retinopathy presents with a retina showing microaneurysms, retinal haemorrhages, hard exudates and cotton-wool spots.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Retinal detachment must be excluded in a patient who presents with symptoms of flashing lights."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"18007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"929"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19148"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19148"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dccff9cb-e78e-410a-850a-06e6deeac38b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dccff9cb-e78e-410a-850a-06e6deeac38b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":437}},{"type":"itemRevision